    ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:1:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:35:"Internet campaigning: Any requests?";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1423:"<p>“CANDIDLY, we go after the cool kids,” confessed Mike Jeffries, the boss of Abercrombie & Fitch, a teenage-fashion retailer, adding, “Are we exclusionary? Absolutely.” These comments, made in 2006, reappeared in an article on May 3rd. They prompted Benjamin O’Keefe, an 18-year-old survivor of an eating disorder, to start a campaign on Change.org, an online-petitions site. He demanded that Mr Jeffries apologise and requested that his store stock clothes in extra-large sizes. About 70,000 web users agreed. On May 21st the retailer invited Mr O’Keefe to a meeting at its headquarters.About 20m monthly visitors make Change one of the biggest of several growing campaigning sites (others include Causes, Upworthy and MoveOn). Launched in 2007, it is responsible for petitions that have helped win health care for victims of water poisoning at an American army base; fought driving-licence corruption in an Indian town; earned the Japanese Olympic women’s soccer team equal treatment to their male counterparts and persuaded authorities in Belarus to investigate animal cruelty.Critics gripe that Change alone did not win these battles. And some of the site’s most popular petitions have not had much effect. Barclays and Citibank were called on by 570,000 signatories to “Condemn Uganda’s ‘Kill the Gays’ Bill”. Another 430,000 demand that China release Liu Xiaobo, an imprisoned Nobel...</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:130:"http://www.economist.com/news/international/21578719-online-petitions-sites-grow-richer-and-more-popular-any