</div>MYTHS die hard. When a handful of feminists protested at the 1968 Miss America pageant in Atlantic City, they burned no brassières. They did, however, dump a few (and make-up and high-heeled shoes) into a “freedom trash can”, while also crowning a sheep.Now the bras are off in earnest. Members of Femen have staged around a hundred topless demonstrations since the group started in Ukraine in 2008, protesting against sex tourism. To add impact they dress as maids and nuns, or don facial hair. Other props include raw meat and fire extinguishers. On May 22nd a protester staged a mock suicide in Notre Dame cathedral in Paris, a day after a far-right historian shot himself there. Her topless torso bore the slogan: “Let fascism rest in hell.”Last year Femen’s “sextremists” gatecrashed Milan’s fashion week to campaign against stick-thin models who—they say—tacitly promote anorexia. This month a Berlin-based activist brandished a burning cross with a crucified Barbie at the opening of a life-size replica of the doll’s house.Such stunts mark a shift away from mainstream feminist causes of legal and economic emancipation: still far from full equality, but with a record of...</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:143:"http://www.economist.com/news/international/21578381-young-feminists-are-reviving-old-struggle-rights-womens-bodies-breast-beating?fsrc=rss|int";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:130:"http://www.economist.com/news/international/21578381-young-feminists-are-reviving-old-struggle-rights-womens-bodies-breast-beating";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"Thu, 23 May 2013 15:05:17 GMT";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0